Douglas C-47 Skytrain: The Carrier of the Divine Soldiers of The Sky

The prelude to today's flight exhibition was revealed by “Dakota“'s take-off driven flown by Andrew Dixon. The paintwork on the fuselage of the aircraft perfectly reproduces the appearance of the D-day, especially the huge black and white stripes herald a bold air strike in the rear of the German army in the hope of cutting off the Nazi reinforcements from reaching the Normandy beachhead. More than 18,000 Allied troops landed on Dakota to fight in the uncertain and decisive battle.

Piper L-4 :Unsung Heroes of D-day

"Grasshopper" help from the very start of the initial invasion. One of the first actions of June 6th, after securing the beach, was to prepare a track of fortune so that they could take off and direct the fire of the Navy and of the Artillery during the breakthrough inland. They were bringing first aid material and pockets of blood to the frontline, and evacuating wounded soldiers. They were delivering radios and ammunition to isolated soldiers, transport maps and strategic messages between the positions of commandments. Duxford brought together three L-4s for a series of formation passes and a tailchase flown by Tom Turner, Mark Petit and Clive Denny.

道格拉斯C-47空中火车（Skytrain，或称空中列车，英文又名Dakota） 是由DC-3民用客机衍生而成的军用运输机，为二战盟军广泛采用的机种之一， 并一直采用至1950年代，时至今日仍然服役于少数国家。 达科塔(英语：Dakota)源于印地安部落达科塔人。
